groupTime373 601.59

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that to find the probability of two independent traits transmitting, one must multiply the probability of one trait by the other. For mutually exclusive traits, one must add the two probabilities. These methods can be used in place of creating time-consuming, large-scale punnet squares to predict genetic outcome. I understand that the Chi Square analysis can be used to assess the validity of such crosses, indicating whether or not outside factors are at work.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that after two gametes have joined together, sexually-reproducing eukaryotes become diploid. Following replication of their number of chromosomes, the cells will divide into two, each new one with an equal amount of mother and father material, making them haploid. A further division results in four haploid daughter cells.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that loci are the points on homologous chromosomes in which corresponding alleles reside. The alleles of two homologous chromosomes may be homozygous (e.g. AA or aa) or heterozygous (e.g. Aa). This variation is just one of the many contributions to genetic variation.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that during meiosis, two phases of cell division occur. The first division, culminated with Telophase I and Cytokinesis, results in two haploid daughter cells with half the genetic material of the original diploid cell.
knowlegeBasis[SQ005] I understand that variability is crucial to the long-term survival and evolution of sexually-reproducing species. Recombination allows pairs of homologous chromosomes to exchange genetic material, creating variability. Reassortment allows the random allotment of genes to daughter cells, creating even more variability.
quantUnderstanding[SQ001] 4 -- Advanced understanding: Could analyze complex scenarios that require knowlege of more subtle points.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] According to Mendel’s second law, genes are independently assorted. This allows us to be able to predict what the ratios of inherited genotypes/phenotypes will be based on the parents’ genotypes. To see if the genes are inherited independently, chi square analysis can be used to compare the observed genotypes of a population to the expected from probability theory and make a conclusion.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Organisms begin the life cycle in the haploid phase as a gamete. The gamete must be fertilized as part of sexual reproduction to enter the diploid phase. The diploid phase of the life cycle is when there are two copies of every chromosome in each cell. The organism then undergoes meiosis and the chromosomes return the the haploid phase.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Alleles are different forms of the same gene. They help increase genetic variability because offspring inherit one allele from each parent. Because alleles can be dominant or recessive, depending on which ones the offspring receives decides what phenotype the offspring will have of that gene.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that meiosis has two phases. The first phase is similar to mitosis. In the first phase the chromosomes duplicate and then homologs pair up. The homologs are then split up and each goes to its respective cell. In the second phase the paired chromatids are separated and there are now four cells each with only half the required genetic material (Haploid).
knowlegeBasis[SQ005] In meiosis there are two steps that help to increase genetic variability. In prophase 1, there is recombination or crossing over. The homologous chromosomes are paired and exchange genetic material between each other. Later in reassortment, the paired homologs are separated and go to different cells with different versions of other chromosomes which also increases the genetic variability.

groupTime373 1753.19

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that certain traits are passed to future generations via alleles on specific loci on chromosomes. The prevalence of certain alleles can be calculated for specific populations, according to the Hardy Weinberg Principle. In addition, Chi Squared analyses provides a measure of statistical significance. This is important because predicted patterns based probability need a way to be "tested" and verified as meaningful.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Sexual reproduction is a process that involves the mixture of genes contributed by two individuals ("parents"). In order for this to take place and produce the correct number of chromosomes in offspring, the male and female individuals must divide in such a way that they will only contribute half of their genes to the next generation. The diploid (2N) phase has the "normal" amount of DNA, while the haploid phase (N) represents just one copy of each gene given by each parent.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that alleles are what determine genetic variation. Alleles are alternate forms of the same genes which correspond to the same aspect of the phenotype of offspring (such as hair or eye color). By having alternate forms of the same genes, there is variation in populations. Having two copies of the same gene not only provide variation, but can also protect against deleterious mutations. Alleles can be dominant, recessive, co-dominant, or show incomplete dominance.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Going off the previous topic of sexual reproduction, meiosis is the specific mechanism that facilitates this transition from diploid (2N) to haploid (N), allowing for sexual reproduction to take place. In non-gamete forming cells, cells divide by mitosis to create an identical copy of the original cell (2N). Meiosis, on the other hand, is a multi-step process that allows for the production of 4 gametes, each with only one copy of each chromosome haploid (N).
knowlegeBasis[SQ005] Meiosis creates variability in two ways. Recombination occurs in metaphase I, when parts of homologous chromosomes crossover, creating more potential gamete combinations than would result otherwise. Without recombination, there would be much less variability, because genes would go together in a block. Reassortment occurs in anaphase I, and provides for independent assortment of genes, meaning inheritance of different factors is independent, increasing variability.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that trait transmission can be predicted based on probability, which is best worked out using a Punnett Square. Test crosses can be monohybrid, dihybrid, trihybrid, and so on. These traits are segregated and therefore the probabilities can be determined by multiplying the chances of each gene from the monohybrid cross. Additionally, a large sample size is best used when using these probabilities because the Chi Square test will show less variance due to chance.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that meiosis is the process of producing haploid gametes while mitosis is the process of replicating diploid cells. I understand that of the several gametes produced only one sperm and one egg will produce a diploid zygote at fertilization.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Alleles can be dominant or recessive for the trait. Homozygous means the homologous chromosomes show both dominant or both recessive traits while heterozygous means they show one dominant and one recessive trait. However, the dominant trait will mask the recessive trait making this organism a carrier for the recessive trait.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] In meiosis, all possible combinations of gametes are formed. In males, sperm is made while oocytes are made in females. However, only one of the four gametes produced in females will actually be grown to full size because the others will disintegrate as polar bodies. Meiosis undergoes two sets of divisions making the chromosomes go from tetrads only two sister chromatids to one chromatid in four different gametes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ005] In prophase I, crossing over occurs between the homologous chromosomes in the tetrad; therefore, the chromosomes can now have DNA from both parents making the potential offspring have traits from both parents. Reassortment occurs in Metaphase I because the tetrads can line up in several different ways making the chromosomes be combined differently.

justifyChoice[justA] A Chi square analysis provides a ratio of an expected phenotype (hypothesis) versus resulting phenotype. In order to experiment with genetics, we need to make hypotheses. These include probabilities in expected phenotypes and using the Chi square, we may be able to justify whether a hypothesis is accepted or rejected.
justifyChoice[justB] When a eukaryote undergoes meiosis, haploidy is met. This haploidy allows for the gamete to fertilize with another gamete of the opposite sex. Fertilization of the two haploid sets allows for the variety of genetic code for each individual organism. Diploid chromosomes may not undergo this recombination because the species needs half the chromosomes from each parent.
justifyChoice[justC] Understanding alleles allow us to predict the probability of phenotypes. Knowing if a certain allele is recessive or dominant and also knowing whether an individual is heterozygous or homozygous for a particular allele can help scientists predict the phenotype and genotype.
justifyChoice[justD] In order for a population to have genetic variation (to drive evolution), offspring must combine or "mix" genetic information from both parents. Meiosis is the mechanism for which this can be achieved. Unlike mitosis, meiosis allows for gametes to form with only half the genetic code (haploidy). Two gametes, each from a parent, combine this genetic information to form a zygote, resulting in diploidy (unique to either parent).

justifyChoice[justA] We can use statistics to determine how likely it is that a phenomenon is due to chance or error. Geneticists use this model to determine how genetypes and phenotypes are passed from one generation to the next. Without this mathematical insight, we would not be able to know with any amount of certainty if our hypotheses were scientifically valid or not.
justifyChoice[justB] The diploid/haploid lifecycle is necessary for sexual reproduction, because in order to create a new organism from two parent organisms, it is necessary to cut the number of chromosomes in the gamete cells of parent organisms in half. This allows the haploid gametes to combine into a zygote with the same number of chromosomes. The alternation between haploid and diploid is therefore essential to passing genetic material on to the next generation (for sexually reproducing eukaryotes, at least).
justifyChoice[justC] Higher plants and animals have two different copies of their genes, located along homologous chromosomes. What makes the copies of genes different is the presence of different alleles at each locus on the homologous chromosomes. Different alleles are important to genetic variation, which makes populations more healthy and stable.
justifyChoice[justD] Meiosis is the process that results in gametes, which have half of the normal number of chromosomes. Without meiosis, sexual reproduction would be impossible, and evolution would be a much, much slower process.

justifyChoice[justA] Probability theory allows a geneticist to predict how the alleles will likely combine in the offspring of a parental generation. This is done by assuming that the genes will undergo independent assortment and each allele has the same probability of being passed to the offspring. Chi Square test allows the geneticist to determine whether the observed results from a genetic cross was likely due to chance or due to something other than chance by comparing the observed and expected values for the ratio of the offspring.
justifyChoice[justB] Sexually reproducing eukaryotes alternate between mitosis, or diploid, and meiosis, or haploid phases of their lifecycle. Without alternating between diploid and haploid phases of the life cycle,sexual reproduction could not occur and lead to later cell growth.
justifyChoice[justC] At the same locus of homologous chromosomes there are alleles which are two variations of the same gene, which can be either the dominant or recessive version of the gene. As the cells reproduce, the alleles are replicated and passed onto the offspring where it recombines with another allele. So alleles are versions of the same gene, which is why they are at the same locus.
justifyChoice[justD] Since meiosis produces cells that will combine with another cell in fertilization then these cells only need to be haploid and thus have half the number of chromosomes that they need. Since meiosis produces four cells from one cell, it creates haploid cells after they go through prophase, metaphase, anaphase, and telophase twice.

knowlegeBasis[SQ005] During prophase 1 of meiosis, the homologous chromosomes pair up and exchange DNA at the formation of the chiasma. This is called recombination based on the exchange of gene fragments. Reassortment is more specific towards the insertion of whole genes. This accounts for the new genetic variability in the daughter cells.

Also, Chi Square analysis can be used to evaluate if there is a significant chance of a certain outcome happening.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] When a two haploid cells combine, the organism created begins life as a diploid zygote, then undergoes mitosis to grow. Once they are able to reproduce, it goes back to the haploid phase of life by creating gametes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Every diploid organism has two copies of every chromosome. Matching chromosomes from each parent are called homologous chromosomes, and since they are the same type of chromosome, they have the same genes at the same spots, or loci, on each chromosome. However, it is possible that they have different forms, or alleles, of these genes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] When cells undergo meiosis, there is a reduction phase, where the homologous chromosomes are split from each other, and each gamete inherits only one copy of each gene, therefore splitting the diploid number of chromosomes for each gamete.
knowlegeBasis[SQ005] During meiosis it is possible for chromosomes to cross-over and exchange information through recombination. Also, the random chance of a gamete inheriting either of each parent's alleles is another source of variability.

knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand the importance of eukaryotes to undergo sexual reproduction in the haploid phase in order to maintain genetic diversity. This diversity leads to evolution of different characteristics for survival. If eukaryotes reproduced in the diploid phase than the number of chromosomes would double each time.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Alleles must occur at the same locus in order for recombination to occur. Also, for all organisms of the same species, if the the alleles were at different loci, then the DNA replicating proteins would not be able to accurately translate the important sections of the genetic code.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Meiosis goes through two phases in order to reduce the number of chromosomes from 2N to N. In this process, recombination and crossing over also occur. Mitosis just replicates the genetic code and the 2 daughter cells are identical with 2N chromosomes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ005] Meiosis creates variability by recombination of genes. Each haploid daughter cell is not identical and each has an equal probability of receiving one of the chromosomes. Mitosis does not create variability because it solely replicates the genes and creates 2 identical daughter cells.
